  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized approaches to combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigations\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition of suspects\n- Cross-border evidence gathering\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk transactions\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Consistent definitions of financial crimes\n- Similar enforcement mechanisms\n- Reduce jurisdictional loopholes\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Financial restrictions\n- Diplomatic pressure\n- Coordinated international investigations\n\n6. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Financial intelligence units\n- International databases\n- Real-time communication networks\n- Tracking complex financial transactions\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering.",
